The paper deals with the problem of answering conjunctive queries against relational databases that may be updated by inserting or deleting tuples. This is a fundamental problem in database theory and falls under the category of database systems (cs.DB). The paper also introduces a new notion of q-hierarchical conjunctive queries and shows how they can be efficiently maintained, which involves data structures and algorithms, falling under the categories of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) and computational complexity (cs.CC). The lower bounds presented in the paper rely on conjectures related to fine-grained complexity, which falls under the category of discrete mathematics (cs.DM). Finally, the paper deals with the problem of counting the number of solutions of k-ary queries, which falls under the category of logic in computer science (cs.LO).
